    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory (use pandas). For each file, produce a compact summary: total row count; min and max timestamp; number of distinct cmdb_id and the list of up to top 20 distinct cmdb_id values; number of distinct KPI/trace/log names and up to top 20 distinct names with their row counts (kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv); for error_logs.csv show up to 10 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, first 120 chars of message). Keep outputs concise and bounded. Return results as a JSON-like dict (not printed tables) so I can inspect available components, KPIs, and time coverage."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric-level anomaly scan found many anomalous points (122,570) across 59 cmdb_id during the incident window. Top candidates by anomaly count include adservice, adservice2, multiple frontend pods, checkoutservice pods, productcatalogservice pods, recommendationservice pods, and cartservice-2. Many top anomalous KPIs are container-level KPIs (cpu, memory, fs, sockets) that reference different nodes (node-5, node-6) but node-* entries did not themselves appear in the top-20 node list. This indicates widespread metric anomalies across many services/pods at the same time window (starting 2022-03-21T16:30:00+08:00). To localize a single root cause we must use traces to find which faulty service/pod is the most downstream faulty component in call chains (trace data covers 16:30–16:59). Therefore the next step is trace analysis to detect anomalous traces (high error_rate, low row_count, high latency) and aggregate by trace source service/pod to identify the most downstream faulty component candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze trace.csv only. For each distinct trace_name compute global P95 and P5 using the full available series for that trace_name. Then, using all trace rows (the file already covers the incident window), mark anomalies as follows: - if trace_name contains 'error_rate' mark rows with value >= P95 as high anomalies; - if trace_name contains 'row_count' mark rows with value <= P5 as low anomalies; - if trace_name contains 'duration_mean' or 'duration_p95' mark rows with value >= P95 as high anomalies. For each anomaly compute severity as (value - P95)/(P95+1e-9) for high anomalies and (P5 - value)/(P5+1e-9) for low anomalies. Aggregate anomalies by trace source component extracted from trace_name (the part after 'trace.from_' and before the next dot, e.g., 'frontend-1'). For each source return: anomalous_point_count, distinct_anomalous_trace_name_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_shanghai, max_severity, and top up to 5 anomalous trace_names with (trace_name, anomaly_count_for_trace_name, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_severity_for_trace_name). Also return total_anomalous_trace_points and number_of_distinct_trace_sources_with_anomalies, and a compact list (up to top 10) of trace sources sorted by anomalous_point_count. Keep outputs compact and bounded (limit rows to top 20). Flag any trace_name that has fewer than 10 total data points in its full series with low_data_flag in the top-trace list."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis found widespread anomalies across nearly all pods (122,570 anomalous metric points across 59 cmdb_id) beginning at 2022-03-21T16:30:00+08:00. Top metric candidates include adservice(s), frontend pods, checkoutservice pods, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, cartservice. Many top anomalous KPI names reference container-level resource issues (CPU throttling, CPU load, memory failures, fs reads/writes, sockets) and some KPI names include node identifiers like 'container.node-6...' or 'container.node-5...', suggesting pods on node-5/node-6 experienced resource anomalies. Trace analysis restricted to the incident window (16:30–16:59) shows many anomalous traces concentrated at frontend-* and checkoutservice-* sources, with high error_rate anomalies (e.g., trace.from_checkoutservice-2.error_rate severity large), and earliest trace anomalies at 2022-03-21T16:30:00+08:00. This pattern (widespread container KPIs + trace-level error spikes across many services starting exactly at 16:30) suggests a systemic resource issue affecting many containers simultaneously — possibly a node-level resource problem impacting pods hosted on that node (e.g., CPU throttling or disk I/O). However, traces show several services faulty; per the diagnosis rules we must use logs to further localize which specific component/resource experienced failures and to confirm whether node-level causes (node CPU/disk) are involved or whether a specific service/pod is the root cause. No final root cause determined yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze log.csv within the incident window 2022-03-21 16:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 17:00:00+08:00. For each cmdb_id compute: total_sum_error_count (sum of value where log_name=='log.error_count'), minutes_with_errors (count of rows with log.error_count>0), earliest_error_timestamp_shanghai (the earliest timestamp in the window with log.error_count>0, or None), and max_error_count in the window. Return a compact table of top 20 cmdb_id sorted by total_sum_error_count with those fields. Additionally, for the top 3 cmdb_id by total_sum_error_count return up to 10 raw log rows each (columns: timestamp_shanghai, cmdb_id, log_name, value) to inspect patterns. Keep outputs bounded and return an empty-table-safe result if no error_count rows are present."
}

Review summary: Metric and trace anomalies all start at 2022-03-21T16:30:00+08:00. Node-localization shows node-6 as the dominant hotspot (56,801 anomalous metric points) with many container KPIs for filesystem reads/writes on /dev/vda. Traces and metrics correlate to pods on node-6, supporting a node-level disk I/O issue that caused widespread service errors.

